ased on the database driver name. Each dialect implements database-specific SQL generation for operations like creating tables, adding columns, creating indexes, etc.\n\n4. **Migration Rollback Handling (migrator.go)**: Rollback handling is implemented through database transactions in the `InTransaction()` method. The method creates a new database session, calls `sess.Begin()` to start a transaction, executes a callback function, and if the callback fails, it calls `sess.Rollback()` to revert all changes. If successful, `sess.Commit()` is called. This ensures that if any migration fails, all changes from that migration are automatically rolled back, maintaining database consistency.\n\nThe framework also supports a flexible migration system defined in `types.go` with the `Migration` interface and various migration types in `migrations.go` including `RawSQLMigration`, `AddColumnMigration`, `AddTableMigration`, `DropTableMigration`, `AddIndexMigration`, `DropIndexMigration`, and `CopyTableDataMigration`. Migration conditions are supported via the `MigrationCondition` interface in `conditions.go` to conditionally execute migrations based on table/column existence checks.\n\nThe migration execution flow is: `RunMigrations()` -> `GetMigrationLog()` -> iterate over migrations -> `doMigration()` -> `InTransaction()` -> `exec()` -> `Rollback()` (on error) or `Commit()` (on success)."
}

